    "translations": {
      "en": {
        "summary": "Imam al-Rida (AS) rules on the ritual purification period required for animals and fish that have been feeding on impure substances (jalal animals). The ruling establishes graded quarantine periods ranging from one day-and-night for fish, to forty days for camels, after which the animal may be lawfully slaughtered and consumed. Al-Sayyari adds a geographic note that the fish ruling specifically applies to Basra, where dung-eating fish were commonly found. This hadith reflects the Shia jurisprudential principle of tahara (ritual purity) as applied to food consumption.",
        "key_terms": {
          "الجلال": "Jalal — an animal that habitually eats human or animal waste/dung, rendering its meat ritually questionable until quarantined",
          "يُنتظر": "To be kept/awaited — the jurisprudential term for the quarantine period (istibraa) required to purify a jalal animal",
          "يُحبس": "To be confined/detained — the animal must be kept away from impure food sources during the quarantine",
          "البصرة": "Basra — the city in Iraq, noted here as the location where dung-eating fish were particularly prevalent"
        },
        "seo_question": "How long must dung-eating animals be quarantined before being slaughtered in Islamic law?"
      },
